{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The content passed to the summary-generation step includes data retrieved from all three sources.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is cross-module handoff: three collectors must all feed one summary input payload. A unit test of a single mapper could pass while wiring drops one source. Real OS/network/subprocess is not required; in-process fakes for the three source clients can reproduce the failure. Rejected higher levels: behavior text is only about payload composition to the summary step, not real infrastructure or model-output quality.","test_description":"Run the real collection/orchestration modules together with deterministic fake clients for metrics, issue tracker, and deployment log. Assert the exact object passed into summary generation contains all three source sections (with expected keys/IDs), so omission at module boundaries is caught.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When one data source is unavailable, the report is produced with a `data unavailable` note for that section rather than aborting.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears when source adapter errors propagate through orchestration and report assembly. This is module interaction/state-handoff, not single-function logic. No real OS/network/subprocess is strictly needed because an in-process fake adapter can raise timeout/connection errors and exercise fallback behavior. Rejected System: behavior does not require validating real network stack semantics; it requires graceful degradation contract across modules. Rejected Agentic/Workflow: no dependence on model judgment or multi-agent sequence.","test_description":"Wire orchestrator + section builders + report renderer with one source client stubbed to fail (e.g., timeout exception) and other two